<br>
I dont think so.  I'm not saying i believe saddam over Bush, Gawd no.  I'm just saying, bush isn't making the best judgment calls about this situation.  I honestly dont see how people can argue with that.  Not even people in the military.  <br>
<br>
I know you have sworn to protect this wonderful country and for that i salute you.  But you all have brains, and are well trained in situational combat.  None of you are drones.  I know you dont want to put down the administration and i know you dont want to believe you will be fighting a meeningless war, but you cant tell me you dont have alarms going off in your head saying this feels wrong... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 585<br> <font color=#333333>(3/10/03 7:30 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: another thing</span><hr size=1> Quick side-notes:  Aybolit, I was using the USSR as an example of deterrence working.  Basically the reasoning is:  if the US + NATO was able to deter a huge military superpower like the Soviet Union...then tell me why they can't deter Saddam.  He poses a minute fraction of the threat, a microscopic dot upon a microscopic dot of a threat that the USSR posed the West.  Yet we deterred them for 50 years, and won't be able to deter Iraq according to Bush &amp; Blair- why?<br>
<br>
Praxx- I don't believe oil is the main reason for the present bellicose stance, but neither do I believe that disarmament is the main reason.  They are both reasons, but secondary to the primary goal of regime change.  That is the only conclusion that fits the analysis of policy, and is one I fundamentally oppose.  Flying in the face of the very principles of international law that allow us to address poverty, hunger, terrorism and international treaties- that is a dangerous game of brinkmanship to play.  Reckless, and totally unecessary is how most people in this country (and a fair few in the US) see the current rush to war.    <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And thank you to the hundreds of thousands of sailors, airmen, troops and Marines for their sacrifice to make our world a safer place. Like or dislike them, you really must admire their courage and commitment. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'll second that- and would suggest that anyone who directs dislike at the military needs their head examined.  I don't dislike them at all- I have the highest respect for them and their charge- which is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>defence of the United States</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  They're willing to risk their lives in the execution of their duty- regardless of personal feelings or misgivings.  That does take a lot of courage and commitment Kad, I agree completely.  Which is why I wish all the forces in the region the very best of luck- if it does come to a war, I'm sure we'll win comfortably- hopefully with a minimum of loss of human life.  But here's the rub- it'd be a lot easier mentally-speaking for our troops (and yours I suspect) to risk their lives under fire if they knew their publics and the international community were behind them.  Those two mandates being unequivocal, fighting effectiveness would (I believe) be improved.  That is why I argue for a policy rethink by the Bush administration around the policies that work and win you friends.  Remember, it's not Saddam that is dividing the international community- but Bush administration policy.  If the administration commits to the due process of inspections then it'd win the friends it needs for military action (if necessary) and after the war for reconstruction and warding off a terrorist counterattack (absolutely necessary).<br>
<br>
  Re-emphasizing the point though: just because I broadly disagree with the idea of pre-emptive action against a nation-state, doesn't mean my admiration for the men &amp; women ready to risk their lives for that policy so far from home is lessened in any way.  Two of my oldest college friends are currently with their unit (42 Commando) on a Royal Marine troopship in the Gulf- they know my stance on pre-emption and agree with me that it's a policy doomed to failure in the long run.  But they will do their duty as staunchly as anyone who believes 100% in the war- because that is a soldier's calling:  duty, courage and self-sacrifice, no matter one's one feelings.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What does my in-game name have to do with the War debate or getting more credibility? A name is a name. Your going to give me more credibility if I'm in AD, MIM or Wudan? Less if I'm in LV, FoH, or Level 5 Frog?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Wrong- I'll give you more credibility if you actually stand behind your words with your real identity.  I couldn't care less what level you are or what guild you are/were in.  I just find it cowardly and spineless when people use an alias to post their thoughts.  I mean, what are you afraid of?  Random tells like you say?  Ever hear of /ignore?  No, you're afraid of something- never mind, I have the easy task of ignoring you-  cowards and spineless jellyfish on the other hand, have to live with themselves.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>snicker. I admire Gandhi and Mandela for what they did, but <br>
PLEASSSE. They were able to achive peace only with the help of international sympathy and pressure.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Would this international pressure be the millions of dollars of trade that the US government had with South Africa?  Or perhaps the complete lack of acknowledgement by any major government of the ANC's cause until the early 1980s.  Perhaps an example of this &quot;overwhelming international pressure&quot; might be the way in which numerous governments including France, the United States and Italy all <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>praised</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the British Raj for the manner in which it was dealing with civil disobedience.  The simple truth was- no major government of note put any practical degree of pressure on either South Africa or the British Raj.  The British government protested loudly in the UN, but still allowed British firms to buy cheap S African diamonds with the blood of miners crushed by apartheid.  <br>
<br>
The victory of these peace movements was down to determination, commitment and unbelievable moral and physical courage.  Determination to stick to the path of peace even when met with violence.  I challenge you to show me a country other than those two which saw emancipation from united and unwilling masters in quite the same way.  It reinforces my point- the easiest route is the force of arms:  the hardest yet fairest path to settlement is the refusal to use them.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>They were strong leaders who had to rebuke violent members of their own organizations. If US leaders turn into Ganhdi or Mandela, we'll be fooked<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Violent members of their own organizations?  Granted there were ANC members who preferred violence, but show me a single significant incident of note where they actually took it.  As for the INC's &quot;violent members&quot;...name one.  Not a single member of the Mahatma's movement favoured or even sought a violent solution.  You seem to know little about either peace movement, trivializing the hardship and self-sacrifice involved in the peaceful route to change.  That attitude disgusts me completely- study the history of it a bit more and then talk to me about it- ignorance is no platform to preach from.<br>
<br>
As for &quot;the US being fooked&quot;- it's funny to note that the closest the Middle East has ever been to a peaceful resolution was with the two presidents most reluctant to commit US forces to a war of aggression.  Carter and Clinton have their critics to be sure- but the amount of conflict resolution they channeled their efforts into certainly puts them closer to the Mahatma or Mandela than it does to Bush's eagerness to commit troops.  I feel Clinton and Carter will in time be remembered for their hard work in achieving peace where they could- remembered alongside those great presidents who had intelligence, character and resolve in abundance.<br>
<br>
America's elder statesmen, the most respected presidents (Adams, Lincoln, Roosevelt)- acted in a moral, just and compassionate manner when faced with the choice of using force, used it as a last resort, and always justified it with a case for war.    Turning to the naive, less statesmanlike alternative for a moment...  When you give an insular, mentally challenged politician like George Bush(Who's the president of Pakistan again?) or Dan Quayle in days gone by (p-ot-a-t-...?) a large hammer like the US military- all their problems tend to look like nails.  Crude perhaps, but it has the ring of truth to an extent.  It requires intelligence, planning and foresight to construct a sound foreign policy that achieves something lasting.  Knee-jerk responses (the post-war scenario in Afghanistan for example) yield nothing but resentment.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Countries would be stomping all over the US, taking advantage of our good nature and we'll soon be assassinated by Saddaem, PLO, Iran, or North Korea. They could care less about wiping out their enemies.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Haha, McCarthy would have been proud.  Just to point out the glaringly obvious- the PLO no longer exists, Iran is very much a US ally in the region atm (how times change), and North Korea is being treated with kid gloves.  None of those nations save North Korea poses a credible threat- and the real threat (N Korea) is actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>deterring the US</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with nuclear weapons.  That must be a bitter pill to swallow, but it's the price of years of diplomatic isolation and neglect.  Saddam doesn't even pose a hundreth of that threat.<br>
<br>
The bottom line here is lurker- that you need to show a constructed case for war.  Basically, you need to show that containment isn't working and that Saddam will not be deterred.  You say that he &quot;could care less about wiping out his enemies&quot;.  <br>
<br>
That's bollocks quite frankly- it's what McCarthy said about the Soviets.  Deterrence worked then, and it works now.  He hasn't touched his neighbours since 1991, the north and south of his country is closed to him:  Kurdish rebels hold the north, Shi'ite village factions hold the south.  Fact is- the USSR had a tonne of nasty weapons too, thousands of times more than Saddam- and that threat was deterred.  Saddam's regime is not suicidal- prove to me that he is either suicidal or a miscalculater.  Fact is, he's an expert at surviving- and there's no way he'd throw that away by launching a WMD attack.<br>
<br>
He's being contained, he's being deterred:  unless you can prove to me that either of these measures have failed substantially- then there is no reason to go to war now.  You've said the international community will &quot;walk away&quot; if we give the inspectors more time.  Well here's the point- the only reason the international community cared two bits for the problem is that the US &amp; UK moved thousands of troops to the region and started typical diplomatic bully-speak.  With over a quarter of a million allied forces encircling Saddam, with several hundred experts combing his country aided by western intelligence- there is no way the international community will walk away unless the US &amp; UK lets them.  To be blunt- containment and deterrence worked even when no one cared a fig for Iraq, even before all those troops mobilized.  It's even more likely to be a successful marriage of measures when attention is focused so rigidly on Iraq as is happening now.<br>
<br>
To summarize- deterrence and containment are working until you prove they have failed lurker.  That is why Clinton continued them as policies, and we haven't had a problem with Iraq since.  Given that these measures work, there is no almighty rush.  Remembering there is no almighty rush- the inspectors, the weapons experts on the ground should be given freedom and space by the US/UK to do their job.  If the inspectors report they can't continue their work, then the US &amp; UK will have 0 problems winning the support they need in the UNSC and disarmament by force will take place.  I remember when Bush, persuaded by Blair and Colin Powell to use the UN route to resolve this.  I find it disgusting, that having committed to the UN route, Bush and Blair are only willing to listen to expert advice if it suits his adminsitration.  Sorry, but the inspectors are the judge of how well Iraq is complying- until they feel their job is impossible there is no need for further action.  <br>
<br>
Prove to me that containment and deterrence have failed lurker.  You've ignored that argument assidiously and I'm pointing it out to you again.  Until these measures have been proved insufficient there is no imminent or forseeable threat and there is no case for war.  .<br>
<br>
I repeat again- the military option isn't going anywhere.  To all of those who maintain that Saddam is playing for time...well so what?  What does that time give him exactly?  I've already shown that he is being contained, and deterrence is there as a safety net.  Nothing is lost with the passage of time if that time is spent with inspections.  If inspections fail, the first people to tell us would be the inspectors.  When that happens- the Security council will line up behind the war option because it will have become the last resort.<br>
<br>
In conclusion- I'm a little fed up with the arguments being used to advocate a war.  It's not about trusting politicians or dictators, not about a ticking clock.  All that matters is that the right policy strategy is adopted.  The most effective strategy has been demonstrated over 12 years:  containment.  It's the most sound strategy legally and morally.  Also- 95% of WMD destroyed were destroyed by inspections:  it's the best system for disarmament that exists.  <br>
<br>
War on the other hand, isolates the very opinion that is needed to fight the global threat of terror.  An international forum with open and clear policy discussion is the only platform to defeat terrorism with.  Al-Qaeda may vanish very shortly, I pray for that every night- but terrorism will not vanish with it.  The fires of extremism, already lit by that brutal bearded murderer currently running for his life in Pakistan...those fires will be fanned to white heat by any war in Iraq.  I have no argument with the American people- indeed I am well aware that opinion is as divided there as it is in this country.  Like Benlian- I simply think war is a hasty, reckless and most importantly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>irrevocable</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> policy step.  Once started, the policy is committed- there's no putting the genie back in the bottle.  Saddam's not going anywhere, can't do anything, wouldn't even if he could(containment + deterrence) and inspections work.  As soon as a credible threat is proven, or inspections fail- there will be a case for war and I'll support it- moreover, so will the rest of the UNSC.  Disarmament must take place- but does it have to take place via a destructive military conflict?  Currently I don't believe that it does, I haven't seen any proof of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>credible</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> threat.   <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
