<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>On top of that Iraq is a barabaric country with no science or technology of it's own<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It's easy to be dismissive, but I'd dispute that.  Before containment measures were applied, they had significant indigenous technology, even if you only examine their military.  Al-Samoud missiles, Khal-Tirya rockets, Iraqi-modified SAMs and Scuds, they have an abundance of technical expertise.  The fact that people are languishing in poverty doesn't preclude arms development to a reasonably high standard- the Soviet Union was living proof of that.  Starvation in numerous provinces for decades, yet a model of technical and military might, for a time.  The system was doomed to collapse in time, as will Iraq's- just as the Soviet Union slipped into decline, so will Iraq under the Ba'ath party.<br>
<br>
And, talking of bloodless victories- Saddam in 12 years under containment has been deemed responsible by Amnesty International for the loss or disruption of 7,000 lives, estimated 2,000 fatalities.  Sounds horrible, and it is- except that the figure is considerably less than China, North Korea, Libya, even Saudi Arabia's government as assessed by Amnesty International.  Worst case scenario- Saddam is contained for another 12 years, inflicts comparable statistics- compare that to a war which will likely claim 100,000 lives or more (see the last Gulf war's casualty listings for a ball-park figure).  This one is likely to be considerably more bloody.  So, not bloodless, I take your point- but certainly less blood-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>y</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than the alternative.<br>
